Not all putters are created equal. Every one requires something a little different. I made my first putter in my parents garage roughly 10 years ago. Since then, we have made more putters than I can count. I can proudly say that every one has been made 100% in house. 

Since the garage days we have always been trying to “catch up.” Realizing that it will probably never happen is a difficult pill to swallow. At the end of the day, you can only do what you can do. As cliche as it sounds…it’s true. 

This year we’re going to make as many putters as we can. Whether it’s 500 or 500,000 the goal still remains the same, to make the best damn putters we possibly can. That’s always been my mindset, and it always will be. The rest will take care of itself.

Custom divot tools for the Cobbtown showdown at Ohoopee. The design was inspired by vintage shotguns. 23 GA represents the year and state of the event. The serial number 30420 is the zip code of Cobbtown, Georgia. 

The top of the tool is inspired by the spine of a shotgun where the metal and wood stock join together. 

In 2018 @gil_hanse took an old onion farm and turned it into one of the finest clubs in the country. I started seeing their Onion logo a few years back and wondering what course it represented. After learning about the club and it’s match play inspired design, I added it to my long list of courses to play. I was pumped when we got the call to work on a project together. 

If you ever the chance to play Ohoopee… Do it! It’s truly a special place.

I have always been a fan of thick blades but I could never line them up very well. 

I wanted to design a wide body that looked sleeker from the top with crispy lines that framed the ball better at address. I tested multiple ideas. 

The end solution was to add an additional step and hard line to the fender section. 

It’s amazing how something so simple can make such a big difference. 

I feel like the result is a great shape for those in between a mallet and a blade. 

What do you think? #LambCrafted
